Thank you for all who joined us for today’s IG Live where @ihadamiscarriage and I spoke openly about the various components of grief and loss.

Our conversation included: 

*Jessica’s personal experience with pregnancy loss.

*How to support someone who has experienced loss.

*Ways to access support for grief.

*The importance of normalizing the grieving process.

Thank you @ihadamiscarriage for being so courageously open and transparent about your healing journey.

Today I had the opportunity to speak about panic attacks with @anxietyjosh, a UK psychotherapist and author.

Our conversation included:
*What are panic attacks?
*The physiological and psychological components of panic attacks. 
*The effectiveness of graded exposure.
*How to shift from avoidance and fear to curiosity and understanding.

Thank you so much for all who joined us and contributed to this fruitful conversation! 

#anxiety #panicattack #mentalhealth

For Day #15 of the December Mental Health Instagram Live Series I got to speak with @refugeingrief about the topic of grief.

Our conversation included:

*Societal ideas about grief
*What does “being stuck” in grief mean.
*The importance of understanding the language we use around grief.
*Ways to normalize grief:

Thank you all who joined us today and each day of this wonderful month dedicated to mental health awareness!

#grief #griefjourney #loss

#trauma #healing #traumainformed

Thank you for all who participated and submitted questions prior to today’s live!

#depression #mentalhealthawareness #askforhelp

For Day #8 of the December Mental Health Instagram Live Series I had the opportunity to speak with Eric @samehere_global about our shared advocacy work to change the conversation around mental health.

Our conversation included: 
*Why the current 1 in 5 statistic divides 
*How emotional & mental health education is currently being implemented in schools
*New ways to raise awareness 
*How to start shifting the conversation from illness to normalizing the fact that we all struggle.

Thank you for everyone who joined and helped facilitate this great conversation!

#samehere #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealth

node.text:
The wildly popular young adult novel where the high school student leaves a scavenger hunt of cassette tapes outlining her reasons for suicide. 

The television series where main character’s anxiety is portrayed as a cute little quirk. 

The emaciated model in designer clothes plastered all over the magazines at the grocery store checkout line.

The edgy, bad boy in your favorite movie who abuses substances yet his lovers find him irresistible and intriguing.

The media (and society as a whole) needs to collectively stop romanticizing mental health struggles. 

There is a distinct line between raising awareness and perpetuating the idea that struggling with your mental health is a desirable state to be in. 

The prettification of mental health challenges misrepresents and further invalidates what millions of people truly struggle with each and every day.

So here is your midweek reminder that mental health struggles are NOT trendy, cute, glamorous or edgy. 

Normalize all mental health struggles, romanticize none. 💚

node.text:
I’m not sure who needs to hear this but you are the allowed to be the first in your family to go to therapy.

I’ve lost count of the number of times that I have heard the phrase “We don’t do therapy in our family.”

Mistrust of medical professionals, belief that therapy is reserved for “crazy” people or insufficient resources are all reasons people never seek out therapeutic services.

And guess who was the first person in my own family to go to therapy? Not my siblings. Not my parents. Not my grandparents or those who came before them.

⤏ Me ⤎

So as provider and consumer of therapy, I can honestly tell you that therapy has the ability to change people’s lives.

Make that phone call.
Address your mental health needs.
Learn healthier coping skills.
Heal that intergenerational trauma.

You have the power to be the one that breaks the cycle of struggling in silence. 💚

node.text:
Alright party people hear me out on this one.

One of the biggest themes I see in the therapy room is people’s attempt to discredit mental health struggles on the basis that “good days” exist.

Just because someone experiences depression doesn’t automatically mean that don’t have the ability to laugh and play.

Just because someone experiences anxiety doesn’t automatically mean they don’t have days where their anxiety feels more manageable. 

Yet we weaponize people’s good days and tell them, “You can’t be that depressed because I saw you at that party last night” or “If you were really struggling then you wouldn’t be able to play sports.”

The fact of matter is that good days exist even when we struggle with our mental health and should be celebrated, not used against us.

We should be saying “I am so glad you were able to go to that party last night because I know things have felt hard lately” or “I am really proud that you are still showing up to soccer practice even on your anxious days.” 

A gentle reminder that having good mental health days doesn’t mean people aren’t still struggling, it means they have moments where life doesn’t feel as burdensome or heavy. 💚

That means by the time you finish reading this post another life is lost.

I refuse to sit in silence about something that kills over 700,000 people EVERY year.

Please join me in raising awareness around this global crisis.

Please join me in engaging in deeper conversations around mental health and suicide.

Please join me in advocating for more accessible mental health services.

Please join me in voting for legislation that funds mental health treatment.

We know how to decrease the number deaths related to suicide, now it’s time to put it into ACTION.

Each one of us plays a role in suicide prevention. 

Will you do your part?

node.text:
Outside of chronic or invisible medical conditions, there still exists a HUGE discrepancy between how we respond to people with physical versus mental health challenges.

A midweek reminder that mental health stigma still very much exists and can be seen at every stage from prevention to treatment. 

Let’s be the generation that ends stigma once and for all so that those who follow never feel forced to struggle in silence. 💚

*It feels important to note that physical challenges and conditions are also subjected to stigma and prejudicial treatment. This post is not negating that but trying to highlight the difference between when our leg is broken (which is debilitating) vs our panic attacks become overwhelming (also which is also debilitating but not taken as seriously).

node.text:
Prioritizing your mental wellbeing means taking inventory of the things that positively and negativity impact it.

The people we interact with on a regular basis absolutely impact our mental health, either by being sources of support or sources of emotional distress.

No one tells us that it’s okay to emotionally distance, limit communication and/or remove the people in our life that are negatively impacting our mental wellbeing

So we stay and we subject ourselves to ongoing mental and emotional pain.

A gentle reminder that you no longer have to continue relationships with people who are detrimental to your mental health. 

Start paying attention to those around you and note the way you feel before, during and after time spent together.

I was 22 years old the first time I lost a loved one to suicide.

He was my godfather and without a doubt my favorite human being.

It took me losing a family member to finally understand that the things I was taught about suicide were untrue.

We unfortunately still live in a society where suicide is labeled as “selfish” or “weak.”

In honor of National Suicide Prevention week, let’s commit to finally changing the conversation around suicide. 

Let’s humanize those who struggle with it.

Let’s offer support over judgement.

Let’s dedicate time to learn and educate ourselves about suicide.

I truly believe suicide is preventable but first we have to shift the way we think and talk about it. 

Let today be the day for each of us to do a little more to end the shame and stigma associated with suicide. 💚

#nationalsuicidepreventionweek #realconvo @afspnational @crisistextline @800273talk

node.text:
Life is not a competition of struggles.

There is no such thing as the pain Olympics.

So then why do we continue to discount other people’s pain by reminding them that others have it worse?

Each of our emotional experiences are valid regardless if other people have it better or worse than us.

So here is your midweek reminder that your feelings matter.

Your sadness matters.

Your happiness matters.

You matter. 💚

node.text:
It’s hard for me to wrap my head around why we as a society continue to blame, judge or shame people who experience trauma.

No one chooses to be traumatized.

A trauma response occurs after we undergo events that overwhelm our system and hinders our ability to cope. 

Yet people continue to treat others as if they are choosing to struggle, with comments like “It’s not that big of a deal” or “Stop focusing on the past.” 

We need to stop shaming people who are trying to survive something that has greatly impacted them.

We need to stop judging people who are trying to manage intrusive thoughts, feelings and memories.

We need to stop blaming people who are struggling to find remnants of who they were before the trauma. 

I can’t stress this enough.

People don’t CHOOSE to be traumatized, so let’s stop treating them as if they do.
